description:
Day 7 and final day of one of the greatest vacations ever! Full journal of nature adventures here: http://www.inaturalist.org/journal/sambiology/9891-vacation-in-california-news-flash-i-like-california

Using the great existing observations from the San Francisco Bay area and species guide to help with the ID's -- but please correct me if I've goofed. Almost ALL of these organisms were new for me!

Elizabeth was learning to drive a 1927 Packard (her father has a 1929 model A that she wants to learn to drive), so we all went to this parking lot for lessons.  I didn't drive -- instead, I observed some of the weeds outside.  :)
place_guess: Mill Valley, California

description: Dying pup. We watched it all day from afar, noticing it at 8am when we were on the other side of the cove collecting seaweed. By midafternoon it had fallen off the rock it was on, turned upside-down covered in sand and flies started flying into its mouth. Still no mother. Surprisingly the Bodega Bay Marine lab wouldn't allow Marine Rescue to assist even though the pup was obviously in distress and easily accessible. Marine Rescue was called, had someone available in the area, and a volunteer who works at the lab, but were denied access even as the vultures flew in to wait on a nearby rock. A shame actually, and hard to watch it suffer. Couldn't understand the Marine Lab's stance when it is also a wildlife sanctuary. I'm no longer a fan (at least of the lady who stated she was 'too busy' to deal with it)

description:
Removed from house, a little one with long tail went to hummingbird garden.  Could be same one already removed from house.  There were 2 larger lizards in the oregano and so I didn't release him there.  This one was in the track of the sliding patio door.
Tuesday after this observation, too late, a little lizard was seen in the same door track that had been moved.  He backed up further under the door.  I don't know if he made it out or died under there.
A different little lizard with a tail regenerating and bent at the tip, was close to the sliding door, outside, found under the dogs water bowl, twice.
Counting the one removed from the garage, that makes 4 (at least one repeat) inside very recently.  The weather is warm and the grass is wet with dew in the morning.  There is a shallow dish of water in the garden, away from the house.

description: Spent the day with the CA140s. The first orca in this photo is Emma, the pod's matriarch (Note the notches in her dorsal for which she is named!). The pod was split up at first, we  watched one group - with Emma's daughter and grandcalf) hunt two fur seals. They then took off in a straight line for eight miles  to join Emma's group - during which this photo was taken.
